## What happened

Apple's security frameworks (Security.framework / CryptoKit) dropped DSA support, and .NET has been progressively aligning with platform-native crypto. In .NET 11, `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS — the platform simply no longer provides a DSA implementation for .NET to wrap.

Linux and Windows are unaffected because OpenSSL and Windows CNG still support DSA.

## How to fix it

Since you only need **verification** of legacy signatures (not signing), the cleanest cross-platform fix is to use **BouncyCastle** (`Portable.BouncyCastle` or `BouncyCastle.Cryptography`):

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

Then replace the built-in DSA verification:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 10) — breaks on macOS in .NET 11
using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
```

```csharp
// After — works everywhere
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);
var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);
verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

**Alternatively**, if you want to keep using the built-in APIs on platforms that support them and only fall back on macOS:

```csharp
bool VerifyDsa(byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] data, byte[] signature)
{
    if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    {
        using var dsa = DSA.Create();
        dsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);
        return dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);
    }
    // BouncyCastle fallback for macOS
    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);
    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
    verifier.Init(false, keyParam);
    verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

**Long-term**: consider migrating away from DSA entirely — it's a legacy algorithm. ECDSA or EdDSA are the modern replacements with full cross-platform support.
